<p><a name="Notes_and_references" id="Notes_and_references"></a></p>
<h2><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Brahman&amp;action=edit&amp;section=11" title="Edit section: Notes and references">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Notes and references</span></h2>
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-0"><b><a href="#cite_ref-0" title="">^</a></b> <cite style="font-style:normal" class="book" id="CITEREFBrodd2003">Brodd, Jefferey (2003). <i>World Religions</i>. Winona, MN: Saint Mary's Press. <a href="/wiki/Special:BookSources/9780884897255" class="internal">ISBN 978-0-88489-725-5</a>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=World+Religions&amp;rft.aulast=Brodd&amp;rft.aufirst=Jefferey&amp;rft.au=Brodd%2C+Jefferey&amp;rft.date=2003&amp;rft.place=Winona%2C+MN&amp;rft.pub=Saint+Mary%27s+Press&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-88489-725-5&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Brahman"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-1"><b><a href="#cite_ref-1" title="">^</a></b> <a href="/wiki/Krishna._The_Supreme_Personality_of_Godhead" title="Krishna. The Supreme Personality of Godhead" class="mw-redirect">Krishna. The Supreme Personality of Godhead</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-2"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2" title="">^</a></b> Veda means 'knowledge' and not merely epistemic knowledge but knowledge of the eternal truth that one's ultimate nature is pure consciousness and independent of material form (cf. <a href="/wiki/Gnosis" title="Gnosis">Gnosis</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-3"><b><a href="#cite_ref-3" title="">^</a></b> Aitareya Upanishad 3.3</li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4" title="">^</a></b> Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 4.4.5,</li>
<li id="cite_note-5"><b><a href="#cite_ref-5" title="">^</a></b> Brihadaranyaka Upanishad 1.4.10,</li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6" title="">^</a></b> Chhāndogya Upanishad 6.8.7 et seq.</li>
<li id="cite_note-7"><b><a href="#cite_ref-7" title="">^</a></b> Chhāndogya Upanishad 3.14.1</li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8" title="">^</a></b> <i>Nrisimhauttaratāpini</i>, cited in Swami Nikhilananda, <i>The Upanishads: A new Translation</i> Vol. I.</li>
<li id="cite_note-9"><b><a href="#cite_ref-9" title="">^</a></b> In the Bhagavad Gītā, <a href="/wiki/Krishna" title="Krishna">Krishna</a> also describes the nature of Brahman. For example, he says "And I am the basis of the impersonal Brahman, which is immortal, imperishable and eternal and is the constitutional position of ultimate happiness" (brahmano hi pratishthaham...) <a href="http://bhagavadgitaasitis.com/14/27/en1" class="external text" title="http://bhagavadgitaasitis.com/14/27/en1" rel="nofollow">B-Gita (As-it-Is) 14.27</a> Translation by <a href="/wiki/A._C._Bhaktivedanta_Swami_Prabhupada" title="A. C. Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada">A. C. Bhaktivedanta Swami Prabhupada</a></li>
<li id="cite_note-neuter-10">^ <a href="#cite_ref-neuter_10-0" title=""><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-neuter_10-1" title=""><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> Not Masculine or Feminine (see <a href="/wiki/Grammatical_gender" title="Grammatical gender">Grammatical gender</a>).</li>
<li id="cite_note-11"><b><a href="#cite_ref-11" title="">^</a></b> <a href="http://srimadbhagavatam.com/sb" class="external free" title="http://srimadbhagavatam.com/sb" rel="nofollow">http://srimadbhagavatam.com/sb</a> Bhaktivedanta VedaBase: Śrīmad Bhāgavatam</li>
<li id="cite_note-12"><b><a href="#cite_ref-12" title="">^</a></b> Anantanand Rambachan, <i>The limits of scripture: Vivekananda's reinterpretation of the Vedas.</i> University of Hawaii Press, 1994, pages 125, 124: <a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=b9EJBQG3zqUC&amp;pg=PA124&amp;dq=brahma+as+opposed+to+brahman&amp;lr=#PPA124,M1" class="external autonumber" title="http://books.google.com/books?id=b9EJBQG3zqUC&amp;pg=PA124&amp;dq=brahma+as+opposed+to+brahman&amp;lr=#PPA124,M1" rel="nofollow">[1]</a>.</li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13" title="">^</a></b> api - but, samradhane - intense worship, pratyaksa - as directly visible, anumanabhyam - as inferred from scripture</li>
</ol>
